    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_938898867" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/938898867" />
    <a title="Zanna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna"><img alt="Zanna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512813535p2/22591633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/938898867?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zanna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zanna" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna">Zanna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Zanna by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/7915003-garima">Garima</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=translated">translated</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=100bestwit">100bestwit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=2015year-reading-women">2015year-reading-women</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer938898867" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6697731920888113870">Well I am outraged. How is it that I was enticed, indeed tricked into reading this book?<br/><br/>I read to decolonise my mind. Who is Hadrian? Hadrian is the arch colonist, one whose belief in the glory of empire is totally unclouded and unshakeable, Emperor of Rome itself. I read to amend the faults of my education in its neglect of racialised &apos;others&apos;, gender outlaws, the materially deprived, all women and whoever else has been mis or under or not represented, in other words the black brown queer trans</span>
  <span id="freeText6697731920888113870" style="display:none">Well I am outraged. How is it that I was enticed, indeed tricked into reading this book?<br /><br />I read to decolonise my mind. Who is Hadrian? Hadrian is the arch colonist, one whose belief in the glory of empire is totally unclouded and unshakeable, Emperor of Rome itself. I read to amend the faults of my education in its neglect of racialised 'others', gender outlaws, the materially deprived, all women and whoever else has been mis or under or not represented, in other words the black brown queer trans crip female poor rabble of the world, and who is Hadrian? Hadrian is the foundational privileged liberal white man! (However, he is a raging homo.) What am I reading?! I asked myself, disgusted. I hate the bloody Romans!<br /><br />But after a few pages it was clear that Hadrian shared my distaste for decadent debauchery at the expense of the many and for wanton violence. Just like me, he prefers the Greeks, slave-keeping and woman-oppressing......aside. I don't really want to put that aside but after all this isn't my book.<br /><br />It's Marguerite's book! And to skip to the back, Marguerite has lived Hadrian, served his story to the depth that he lives because she is living, because of her Hadrian has become a Frenchwoman, is performing this biography in drag, calling for liberte and humanite to rule and endure in the empire. She effaces herself with a grace that cannot be ignored.<br /><br />Hadrian goes back in memory to glory days when everything was peachy, not least his teenage lover Antinous, whose loss could not possibly have been mourned more extravagantly... Wait did I just breezily sail over an incident of child abuse? Hadrian is getting intoxicated, drunk in love, inebriated by power and adoration, and by this point, the hundredth page or so, I'm completely seduced, like Marguerite's wine slipped into my camomile tea and I'm too entranced to taste the difference. It's interesting that the moment I all but gave up resisting the pull was the occasion of a remark on religion, since in the <i>notes</i> Yourcenar speaks of being inspired by Flaubert's astute comment that Hadrian's moment was a lonely one for 'man' [sic], between one set of gods and the next. Hadrian is not exactly godless; in fact he embraces the variegated backdrop of religious mysteries that animate the hills and forests of Rome and the arid islands of Greece. His comments on astrology delighted me (see later), while his bizarre persecution of the Jews seemed motivated by a distaste for their style of religious devotion.<br /><br />Certainly racism is at play, often in the “some of my best friends are [...]” mode, but Hadrian's apparent disdain for 'Orientals' (there are some particularly unpleasant remarks about a mixed-race Roman) didn't hinder his making peace with the Persians and seeking to serve in their realms, as in his own, the common good. He decries the Jews as fanatics and ignores their wishes, leading to escalating hostilities. As often, I had to remind myself that Yourcenar was writing to understand Hadrian, not eulogise him, explain his actions rather than justify them, but this aspect rankled more than others that were also problematic. A few nice personal inclusions do counter the negativity.<br /><br />I know I've failed to explain why I'm giving this book five stars but it's like trying to explain why cake is delicious, or what it feels like to win a prize. Books cast spells, and to this one I turned out to be susceptible.<blockquote>Almost everything that men have said best has been said in Greek. There are, I know, other languages, but they are petrified, or have yet to be born</blockquote>Here Hadrian reveals the limits of his thought (vaunts the superiority of a language he knows that mediates a culture he has experienced) as well as the strength of his admirations for the Greeks<blockquote>I doubt if all the philosophy in the world can succeed in suppressing slavery; it will, at most, change the name. I can well imagine forms of servitude worse than our own, because more insidious, whether they transform men into stupid, complacent machines, who believe themselves free just when they are most subjugated, or whether to the exclusion of leisure and pleasures essential to man they develop a passion for work as violent as the passion for war among barbarous races. To such bondage of the human mind and imagination I prefer even our avowed slavery. However that may be, the horrible condition which puts one man at the mercy of another ought to be carefully regulated by law. I saw to it that a slave should no longer be anonymous merchandise sold without regard for the family ties which he has formed, or a contemptible object whom a judge submits to torture before taking his testimony, instead of accepting it upon oath. I prohibited forced entry of slaves into disreputable or dangerous occupations, forbidding their sale to brothel keepers, or to schools of gladiators. Let only those who like such professions practice them; the professions will but gain thereby.</blockquote>This passage strikes me as mask-slippage on Yourcenar's part, or a knowing examination of what her Hadrian would make of contemporary forms of alienation. He uses racist ideas to express his position ('war among barbarous races') that the form of slavery on which the comfort of the Greek and Roman ruling classes depends is not so bad. He mentions some of his ameliorating reforms. It's nice that he mentions sex work as a profession, but it is dubious that people choose such work, or that of a gladiator, from a 'liking' for it. We are able to read Hadrian's class privilege when he speaks of his efforts for the perceived common good.<blockquote>I have always been friend to astronomers and client to astrologers. The science of the latter is questionable, but if false in its details it is perhaps true in the total implication; for if man [sic] is part and parcel [anachronistic idiom!] of the universe, and is ruled by the same laws as govern the sky, it is not unreasonable to search the heavens for the pattern of our lives, and for those impersonal attractions which induce our successes and our errors.</blockquote>Hadrian never expresses what I would call religious devotion, but he is decidedly open to the mysterious, and frequently describes ritual experiences as aesthetic gateways to transcendance, much as he does hearing performances of poetry<br /><br />Women play small parts in this epic; the only ones who get more than passing mention are the wife of the former emperor, Plotina, who is one of the chief supporters of Hadrian, helping to secure his adoption in this account, and his wife Sabina. On Plotina's wisdom and intelligence he waxes lyrical, while he has nothing good to say about Sabina. He dwells on her unattractiveness more than any other quality. She seems to have an interesting collection of friends and I rather wanted to read her biography too, perhaps in part to see Hadrian through another pair of female eyes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6697731920888113870" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


